│ stop({"edit_points": [[381, 388,                                              │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopPredication.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.           │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs due to an assertion failure inside │
│ ScalarEvolution::isLoopEntryGuardedByCond which requires both SCEV operands   │
│ to be available at loop entry (isAvailableAtLoopEntry).                       │
│ LoopPredication::expandCheck calls isLoopEntryGuardedByCond when it only      │
│ verifies that the operands are loop invariant (SE->isLoopInvariant), which is │
│ weaker than being available at loop entry. In this reproducer,                │
│ ScalarEvolution constructs the RHS as (-1 + %length), where %length is        │
│ derived from an atomic load in a different loop, and SCEV concludes this      │
│ expression is invariant for loop1, but not necessarily available at the loop1 │
│ entry. As a result, the assertion triggers.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe   │
│ scalar-evolution print shows the guard check being processed and derives LHS: │
│ 310 and RHS: (-1 + %length) with Pred: ult. Immediately before the crash,     │
│ LoopPredication's debug logs show it trying to widen the guard and then       │
│ calling SE->isLoopEntryGuardedByCond in expandCheck with both operands        │
│ loop-invariant. The assertion in ScalarEvolution complains specifically that  │
│ RHS is not available at loop entry, which aligns with SCEV using %length      │
│ instead of the lcssa value (%length.lcssa) and with LoopPredication failing   │
│ to enforce availability at entry before querying SE.\n\n3. Root Cause         │
│ Analysis:\nLoopPredication::expandCheck uses SE->isLoopInvariant(LHS, L) and  │
│ SE->isLoopInvariant(RHS, L) to decide whether to fold the guard into          │
│ constants by calling SE->isLoopEntryGuardedByCond. However, loop invariance   │
│ in SCEV does not imply the expression is available at the loop entry block;   │
│ values can be invariant but still computed inside the loop or depend on       │
│ definitions that do not dominate the preheader/entry.                         │
│ isLoopEntryGuardedByCond asserts that both operands are available; since      │
│ expandCheck does not check availability, it can call into ScalarEvolution     │
│ with operands failing that requirement, causing the assertion.\n\nIn this     │
│ reproducer, RHS simplifies to (-1 + %length), and SCEV marks it invariant for │
│ loop1, but it is not available at loop1 entry according to SCEV's             │
│ availability check, hence the assertion.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe    │
│ should harden LoopPredication::expandCheck to only call                       │
│ ScalarEvolution::isLoopEntryGuardedByCond when both operands are available at │
│ loop entry, not just loop invariant. If the availability check fails, expand  │
│ the compare instead of trying to fold to true/false.\n\nEdit at               │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopPredication.cpp lines 381-388:\n- Current      │
│ code:\n  if (SE->isLoopInvariant(LHS, L) && SE->isLoopInvariant(RHS, L)) {\n  │
│ IRBuilder<> Builder(Guard);\n    if (SE->isLoopEntryGuardedByCond(L, Pred,    │
│ LHS, RHS))\n      return Builder.getTrue();\n    if                           │
│ (SE->isLoopEntryGuardedByCond(L, ICmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred),\n       │
│ LHS, RHS))\n      return Builder.getFalse();\n  }\n\n- Replace with:\n  if    │
│ (SE->isLoopInvariant(LHS, L) && SE->isLoopInvariant(RHS, L)) {\n    // Only   │
│ query SCEV's loop-entry guard if both operands are available\n    // at loop  │
│ entry; loop invariance alone is insufficient and may violate\n    //          │
│ isLoopEntryGuardedByCond's preconditions.\n    if                             │
│ (SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry(LHS, L) && SE->isAvailableAtLoopEntry(RHS, L))    │
│ {\n      IRBuilder<> Builder(Guard);\n      if                                │
│ (SE->isLoopEntryGuardedByCond(L, Pred, LHS, RHS))\n        return             │
│ Builder.getTrue();\n      if (SE->isLoopEntryGuardedByCond(L,                 │
│ ICmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred),\n                                        │
│ LHS, RHS))\n        return Builder.getFalse();\n    }\n  }\n\nThis ensures    │
│ the assertion is not hit and preserves the optimization when correct.\n\n5.   │
│ Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to LoopPredication calling                      │
│ ScalarEvolution::isLoopEntryGuardedByCond with SCEV operands that are loop    │
│ invariant but not available at loop entry. Adding an availability check in    │
│ expandCheck prevents violating the preconditions of isLoopEntryGuardedByCond, │
│ avoids the assertion, and maintains correctness by falling back to            │
│ materializing the compare when availability is not guaranteed."})             │
